<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#F0DCA0">Originally posted by Tutamun on 10-03-2000 06:40 PM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">Lar,
do you want to discuss the interface here? I thought about it for a while...

*** *** *** *** ***
[i]Walking : Left click (walk to destination), Left drag (walk in direction)
Running : Press R to toggle between walk/run or drag mouse to the edges of the screen
Talking : Left click on friendly character
Attacking: Left click on enemy character / hold ctrl to attack friendly character
Using an object : Left click on it 
Moving an object : Left drag it
Picking up an object in the inventory rag it on your character, interface bar, left click on it while holding the alt key
Destroying an object:hold ctrl and click on object
Casting a spell:Right click
Using one object on another object : Drag one object on top of the other object[/i]
*** *** *** *** ***

I don't think it will be very good the way you want to do it for a couple of reasons:
1.) left click an object: uses it -and- (left click on enemy: attack -or- left click on ground: walk there)
- In a (hectic) fight you may accidentaly click on a (poison) potion lying on the ground and use (drink) it.
2.) left click an object: uses it -and- left drag an object: move it
- By not holding the mouse button down long enough you will use the object instead of moving it.
3.) (left drag an object: move it -or- left drag an object to character/interface-bar: pick it up) -and- left drag an object onto another object: use object on another object
- Releasing the mouse button too early or too late results in the object being used on another object lying on the grond. What you wanted to do was pick it up or just move it.
- You can not move one object on top of another because one is then used on the other.
4.) left drag an object: move it -and- left drag on ground: walk in that direction
- What happens when you hold the mouse over an object and keep pressing the left mouse button?
- You should start walking in that direction (otherwise it would be hard to walk out of a fight when lots of stuff lies on the ground)
- Now if you want to move the object but "forget" to move the mouse (or don't move it far enough) you will start walking there which is not what you wanted to do.

The problem is that objects get used and moved with the same mouse button. Even walking and attacking is done with this mouse button. This is very bad imho.

Diablo sold very well because it had a pretty good interface. They could have done a few things better, but why don't you stick to the basic Diablo interface and make it better suited for  :div:? Diablo has the problem that you (try to) pick up something when left clicking on it. This is annoying during fights.</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
</table>

